Pago 68. 1. servili tumultu: ‘at the time of the uprising of the slaves.' The gladiators, who were for the most part slaves captured in war, rebelled under SpartacuS, and, with other slaves that flocked to their standards, resisted the Roman arms for three years, Β. c. 73-71. As many of these were of Germanic origin, Caesar here speaks of the Ro- mans having become familiar with the prowess of the Germans in the Servile War. The word tumultus is used instead of bellum in case of any sudden war within the limits of Italy. quos z the antecedent is implied in servili, = servorum.
